did.abstract: The KUHT Records includes correspondence, memoranda, publications, clippings, photographs, and related material dating from the 1950s through the 1990s. The bulk of the material dates from the mid-1960s to 1990s.

bioghist.head: Historical Note:
bioghist.p: KUHT-TV debuted on May 25, 1953, as America's first educational television station. Since then it has served as a model for other educational television stations. Its main goal is to provide quality programming to students, faculty, and the entire community. KUHT predates the Corporation for Public Broadcasting (CPB) and the Public Broadcasting System (PBS). Its history includes award-winning local and national productions, including a national Emmy Award for excellence. KUHT is licensed to the University of Houston, and is located in the LeRoy and Lucile Melcher Center for Public Broadcasting located at 4343 Elgin, on the northeast corner of the main campus.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The KUHT Records includes correspondence, memoranda, publications, clippings, photographs, and related material dating from the 1950s through the 1990s. The bulk of the material dates from the mid-1960s to 1990s.
Please contact the collection curator Emily Vinson (evinson@uh.edu) for further information.

The series in the collection include: Discrepancy Files, Development and Production Files by Jim Fisher and Paul Yeager, Gulf Region Education Television Affiliates (GRETA), Photographs, Ephemera, Awards, Publications, and Scrapbooks.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The FCC requires broadcasters to produce a daily program log on all their broadcasts. If they were to find any variations to the broadcast schedule, they are to produce a document called the Discrepancy Report. The original log is updated with that information to produce an 'As-Run Log.' The FCC no longer requires broadcasters to maintain a hard copy of the 'As-Run Log,' as long as they have an electronic version.

did.unittitle: Development and Production Files - Fisher, Jim

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Jim Fisher worked as volunteer and part-time employee for KUHT during 1983-1991, and worked with Bob Cozens throughout that time. He became full-time in 1991, and assisted in the post-production, and editing of film and video projects. In the late 80s he became the station's Development Producer, the fourth person to hold that position. The job involved producing a number of the station's special projects. A short time later the Development Producer's position was combined with the Promotion group to form the station's first Creative Services Department, also temporarily referred to as Department X. Jim was the first supervisor of the Creative Services Department, and after two years he left that department and became the Senior Producer of Special Projects. Most of Jim's productions now deal with a historical aspect; he is referred to as the "go-to guy" for all things involving KUHT archival holdings. These are Jim Fisher's working production files.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Paul Yeager was hired full-time as Producer at KUHT around 1983 or 1984. Before that he worked part-time as a freelancer prior to becoming a UH employee. Paul worked with Bob Cozens in the KUHT Film Department and produced a number of films with a main focus on the arts, one them being 'Journey To the Sky.' Paul left KUHT in September 1992.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: On February 23, 1965, forty school administrators met to discuss the Gulf Region Educational Television Affiliates known as "GRETA." GRETA was an organization designed to offer educational television to various school districts. A board of school administrators governed the organization. Through the cooperation of school administrators, teachers, and Channel 8 personnel, programs were developed into the school curriculum. In his book, Public Television America's First Station, William Hawes noted, "GRETA materials were primarily considered supplementary to classroom instruction, although in some cases they were dominant." By 1977, GRETA broadcast in-school programming to sixty area school districts.
